</preferred-name><author-url>http://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/6603707659</author-url><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60031004" id="60031004"/></author></dc:creator><dc:description><abstract original="y" xml:lang="eng">
<ce:para>This work addresses potential advancements in integrated gasification combined cycle (IGCC) system, in particular focusing on membranes for gas separation at high temperature. These requirements can be met by metal and ceramic membranes and are reviewed hereinafter. High temperature membrane technology for gas separation is embryonic at this stage. The technology is attracting a large interest by research groups and is currently supported by major funding agencies around the world. Several key areas of interest include novel materials, fabrication process and membrane systems. Novel materials are required to address trace contaminants in dirty syngas processing, in particular the development of palladium alloys to tolerate sulphur. Also water has detrimental effects in many ceramic membranes, and functionalisation of silica surfaces delivers hydrostability. Fabrication processes to reduce film thickness and defects are taking ceramic membrane fluxes to 135 litres (STP) of H <inf>2</inf> per square metre of membrane area per minute, and at 1 atmosphere differential pressure across the membrane, and H<inf>2</inf>/CO<inf>2</inf> selectivity in excess of 50. Palladium membranes show lower fluxes, but H <inf>2</inf>/CO<inf>2</inf> selectivities are several orders of magnitude higher than that for ceramic membranes. Data on the performance of scale up and long term stability of membrane systems integration in IGCC is still scarce, whilst current costs of over US$ 1,000/m<sup>2</sup> of membrane area need to be reduced. From a technological view point, there is no single technology at the moment that can address all the future needs of syngas processing. It is likely that several technologies will address specific functions and requirements for gas separation in coal gasification.</ce:para>
